ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic performance of as-fabricated materials was evaluated by the degradation of tetracycline (TC) under visible light irradiation (Fig. 7
                     a). Before the photocatalytic experiment, the prepared materials were put in the dark adsorption process, and the corresponding adsorption rate can be seen in the Fig. S3, revealing that with the introduction of CDs in the composite, the adsorption effect of ZSO has been obviously enhanced. It is notably that the TC concentration is difficult to be decreased after 60 min of visible light irradiation in the absence of photocatalyst. Conversely, after the introduction of photocatalysts, the concentration of TC decreased significantly under the same condition. The degradation rate of TC by pure ZSO was only 17.03% during 60 min irradiation time. Dramatically, the addition of CDs significantly improved the degradation efficiency of TC, which was closely related to the loading contents of CDs. For example, when the amount of CDs increased from 1 to 3 wt%, the degradation rate gradually increased from 39.08% to 81.76% within 60 min irradiation time, while further increasing the CDs content from 3 to 5 wt% tardily reduced the photocatalytic degradation efficiency from 81.76% to 49.20% (in Fig. 7b). The reason for this phenomenon may be caused by the shading effect. To quantitatively analyze the catalytic efficiency, the Langmuir-Hinshelwood model was applied. Degradation data reveal that the decomposition kinetics of the as-prepared photocatalysts is well fitted agreement with the pseudo-first order kinetics (Fig. 7c). From the Fig. 7d, the optimum photoactivity for CDs-ZSO with CDs mass content of 3 wt% (3% CDs-ZSO) exhibited the highest photodegradation rate constant (0.0231 min−1), which was approximately 21 times than the pristine ZSO (0.0011 min−1). In addition, our proposed CDs decorated porous ZSO cubes composite exhibit the highest photocatalytic activity for the degradation of TC among ever reported composite photocatalytic materials (Table 1
                     ). Subsequently, to investigate the stability of the 3% CDs-ZSO composite photocatalyst, a recycling experiment was performed under the same conditions. As shown in Fig. 7e, after four cycles of operation, the TC photocatalytic degradation rate showed no significant change. Significantly, no apparent crystalline structure and morphology’ s change were observed in the XRD patterns (Fig. 7f) and TEM images (Fig. S4) of the photocatalyst after cyclicing experiment, which fully confirms that as-prepared 3% CDs-ZSO composite photocatalyst exhibited the outstanding structural stability.
